<p>The Google Maps pattern uses a modified <code>iframe</code> embed code from Google within a div wrapper with specific classes to display a map within a main content section.</p>

<p>An embedded Google Map may be used only within these three layout patterns:</p>

<ul>
    <li><a href="../content-whole/index.html">Content whole</a></li>
    <li><a href="../content-halves/index.html">Content halves</a> (single-point only)</li>
    <li><a href="../content-thirds/index.html">Content thirds</a></li>
</ul>

<p>The Google Maps pattern has two main variants: multiple-point and single-point maps.</p>


<h3>Multiple-point maps</h3>

<p>Multiple-point maps must be created using Google <a href="https://www.google.com/mymaps">My Maps</a>; this requires a Google account.</li></p>

<p>See <a href="https://support.google.com/mymaps/#topic=3188329">My Maps Help</a> for information on using My Maps. </p>

<ul>
    <li>You may only embed multiple-point maps using 'Content whole' and 'Content thirds' patterns; you may not use the 'Content halves' pattern.</li>
    <li>You can use whichever marker icons and colours are on offer (within reason), but custom icons must not be used.</li>
</ul>

<h3>Single-point maps</h3>

<p>Single-point maps use standard <a href="https://www.google.co.uk/maps">Google Maps</a>; this does not require a Google account.</p>

<h3>Required HTML</h3>

<p>As part of making the maps responsive, you need to take the 'src' from the embed code given by Google and place within the below HTML:</p>

<pre><code class="pattern-source html"><div class="embed-responsive embed-responsive-16by9 google-map">
	<iframe src="[Embed URL here]" class="embed-responsive-item google-map"></iframe>
</div>
</code></pre>

